revision.text:
{{Infobox person |name = Adolph Otto Niedner |image = |caption = |birth_date = October 1, 1863 |birth_place = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1954|12|27|1863|10|1}} |death_place = [[Dowagiac, Michigan]] |other_names = |known_for = |alma_mater = |occupation = [[gunsmith]] |nationality = {{flag|United States}} }} '''Adolph Otto Niedner''' (1863–1954) was an American [[gunsmith]] remembered for pioneering work with cartridges including the [[.22 Long Rifle]] and [[.25-06 Remington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.massrifle.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=65&Itemid=96|title=Massachusetts Rifle Association History|publisher=Massachusetts Rifle Association|accessdate=2013-02-05}}</ref>
==Early life== Niedner was born in [[Philadelphia]] to [[Germans|German]] immigrants Carl Heinrich Niedner and Augusta W. (Trapp) Niedner. He enlisted in the [[United States Army]] in 1880 and fought against the [[Apache]] uprisings led by [[Victorio's War|Victorio]] and [[Geronimo]]. He was discharged in 1883 with a scar from a scalp wound. He served on the [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]] police force until moving to [[Malden, Massachusetts]] in 1899 to work as a [[weaving|weaver]] in his father's business manufacturing [[linen]] [[sock]]s.<ref>[[The Herald-Palladium|''News-Palladium'']] 28 December 1954 p.13</ref>
==Gunsmith== Niedner opened a gunsmith shop in Malden in 1906. Niedner worked with members of the [[Massachusetts Rifle Association]], including [[gun barrel]]-maker [[Harry Pope]], making tools and rifles for [[ballistics]] expert [[Franklin Ware Mann]], and prototype Patridge [[sight (device)|gun sights]] for inventor Eugene Patridge. Niedner moved to [[Dowagiac, Michigan]] in 1920 to establish the Niedner Rifle Company, and was elected [[mayor]] of Dowagiac in 1926. Niedner specialized in [[Chamber (firearms)|chambering]] and [[single-shot]] rifles. Niedner manufactured custom rifles for many noted riflemen including [[Townsend Whelen]], [[Charles Newton (inventor)|Charles Newton]] and [[.257 Roberts|Ned Roberts]].<ref>Barsness, John "A Pair of .26-06s" in August-September 2012 ''Handloader'' p.37</ref> Niedner sold the business following the death of his wife, Josephine C. (Josie), in 1940; and lived alone in Dowagiac until death from a heart attack on 27 December 1954.<ref>''[[Traverse City Record-Eagle]]'' 28 December 1954 p.15</ref>
