{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2016}} {{Infobox politician | name = Michael Appleby | image = Michael Appleby.jpg | alt = | caption = | candidate = | election_date = | runningmate = | opponent = | incumbent = | birth_date = <!--- {{birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} ---> | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | party = [[Aotearoa Legalise Cannabis Party]] | otherparty = | relations = | spouse = | civil partner = | children = | residence = [[Wellington]], New Zealand | occupation = [[Lawyer]], cannabis activist | religion = | signature = | signature_alt = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Michael Appleby''' is a politician, [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] activist, and lawyer based in [[Wellington]], New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/crime/3630003/Drug-swoop-targets-national-shop-chain |title=Drug swoop targets national shop chain |first1=Britton |last1=Broun |first2=Kate |last2=Newton |newspaper=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]] |publisher=[[Fairfax New Zealand]] |date=28 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5uxlmIUhf?url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/crime/3630003/Drug-swoop-targets-national-shop-chain |archivedate=14 December 2010 |accessdate=14 December 2010}}</ref>
==Background== Appleby is a [[human rights]] lawyer with a B.A. in politics and English, and an M.A. in Administrative Law, Taxation and Trusts, and Constitutional Law. He has taught Law at various universities around New Zealand and Australia.<ref name="WCC profile 2013">{{cite web|title=Candidate - Michael Appleby|url=http://wellington.govt.nz/have-your-say/elections/election-2013/candidates/michael-appleby|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325152045/http://wellington.govt.nz/have-your-say/elections/election-2013/candidates/michael-appleby|dead-url=yes|archive-date=25 March 2014|work=wellington.govt.nz|publisher=Wellington City Council|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>
==Political career== In addition to his legal career, Appleby was the leader of the [[Aotearoa Legalise Cannabis Party]] from its foundation in 1996 until 2013.<ref name="WCC profile 2013" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Elder |first=Vaughan |title=Dunedin man elected to lead cannabis party | url=http://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/276893/dunedin-man-elected-lead-cannabis-party |date=14 October 2013 |accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref> This small [[political party]] is dedicated to the relaxation or repeal of laws against the use of cannabis and has never been represented in Parliament.
Appleby has stood as his party's candidate in the {{NZ electorate link|Wellington Central}} electorate since its inception in 1996. His best result was in the [[New Zealand general election, 1999|1999 election]] where he gained third place, aided by the fact that most major candidates had pulled out to support either incumbent [[Richard Prebble]] or challenger [[Marian Hobbs]]. He came fifth in the [[New Zealand general election, 2011|2011 election]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.electionresults.org.nz/electionresults_2011/electorate-59.html |title=Official Count Results -- Wellington Central |publisher=Elections New Zealand |date=10 December 2011 |accessdate=5 June 2013}}</ref> He later represented the Aotearoa Legalise Cannabis Party in the [[Ikaroa-Rāwhiti by-election, 2013|2013 Ikaroa-Rāwhiti by-election]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO1306/S00020/aotearoa-legalise-cannabis-party-launch-by-election-campaign.htm |title=Aotearoa Legalise Cannabis Party launch By-Election campaign |publisher=Scoop.co.nz |date=4 June 2013 |accessdate=5 June 2013}}</ref>
Appleby stood unsuccessfully for the [[Wellington City Council]] in October 2004.<ref>{{cite web|last=Farrar |first=David|title=Full Wellington City Council results |url= http://www.kiwiblog.co.nz/2004/10/full_wellington_city_council_results.html|work=Kiwiblog|date=23 October 2004 |accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref> He ran again for the Wellington City Council in the October 2013 [[Wellington local elections, 2013#Lambton ward|local government elections]], where he placed ninth in the Lambton Ward and was not elected.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael Appleby|url=http://www.vote.co.nz/2013/candidates/michael-appleby-8808|work=Vote.co.nz|publisher=Local Government New Zealand|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lambton Ward |url=http://wellington.govt.nz/have-your-say/elections/election-2013/results-and-voting-documents-returned/lambton-ward |publisher=Wellington City Council|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref>
