{{Infobox climber | name = Renata Chlumska | image = Renata Chlumska 2.JPG | image_size = | alt = | caption = Renata Chlumska at the Swedish release of Saving Mount Everest | nickname = | nationality = Swedish and Czech | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1973|12|09}} | birth_place = Malmö, Sweden | death_date = | death_place = | residence = Jönköping, Sweden | education = | occupation = Adventurer and Mountain Climber | height = <!-- {{convert|}} (yyyy) --> | weight = <!-- {{convert|}} (yyyy) --> | retired = | website = {{URL|http://renata.nu/}} | typeofclimber = | highestgrade = | highestredpoint = Mount Everest 8850 Meters | highestonsight = | highestboulder = | knownfor = First Swedish and Czech woman to climb Mount Everest. | firstascents = | namedroutes = | majorascents = | worlds = | medaltemplates = | show-medals = | updated = 13 January 2015 }}
'''Renata Chlumska''' (born December 9, 1973 in [[Malmö]], Sweden) is an [[adventurer]] and [[mountain climber]]. Born to [[Czechs|Czech]] parents, she has both [[Swedes|Swedish]] and Czech citizenship.
In 1999, she became the first Swedish and Czech woman to climb [[Mount Everest]]. During 2005 and 2006 she performed a challenge called "Around America Adventure" in the [[lower 48]] states of the United States.<ref>[http://www.nationalgeographic.com/adventure/0308/q_n_a_chlumska.html "National Geographic Adventure Mag.: Q&A with Swedish Mountaineer Renata Chlumska"] ''National Geographic'', August 2003. Retrieved January 13, 2015.</ref> She paddled a kayak from [[Seattle]] to [[San Diego]], bicycled with the kayak on a carriage from San Diego to [[Brownsville, Texas]], continued kayaking around [[Florida]] to [[Eastport, Maine]], and then bicycled back to Seattle. She became the first person to circumnavigate 32 states by bicycle and kayak.<ref>[http://seattletimes.com/html/outdoors/2003261337_kayak16m.html "Around America, by land and by sea"] ''The Seattle Times'', September 18, 2006. Retrieved January 13, 2015.</ref>
She was engaged to [[Göran Kropp]] when he died in a climbing accident.
