'''Robert K. C. Forman''', a long-term TM-practitioner and a critic of the constructionist approach to [[mystical experience]], was professor of religion at the City University of New York, author of several studies on religious experience, and co-editor of the [[Journal of Consciousness Studies]].

==Biography==
Forman is a long-term [[Transcendental meditation]] practitioner, with over 40 years of practice.<ref group=web name="bio">[http://enlightenmentaint.com/author/ http://enlightenmentaint.com/, ''About Robert K.C. Forman'']</ref> After two years of practice he had his first "break-through" during a nine-month meditation retreat:<ref group=web name="bio" /> 
{{quote|On January 4, 1972, at about 4 in the afternoon, the back of my neck zipped itself into extinction.   I was on a 9 month Transcendental Meditation retreat, meditating and doing Yoga for about 8 hours daily.  Even though I was hyper vigilant about inner shifts there, I could not have missed it.  Who I was, how I thought, how I saw, even how I would sleep from that night on were now, and would remain ever after, different.<ref group=web>[http://studyspiritualexperiences.weebly.com/robert-forman.html The Alister Hardy Society for the Studdy of Spiritual Experience, ''An Experience – and Disappointment – of ‘Enlightenment’ '']</ref>}}

This initial experience led him to pursuing a PhD at Columbia University, and an academic career in religious studies.<ref group=web name="bio" />

==Academic career==
Forman has worked as professor of religion at City University of New York, both Hunter College and City College, and is Founding Executive Director of The Forge Institute for Spirituality and Social Change. His books include ''The Problems of Pure Consciousness'', ''The Innate Capacity'' and "Enlightenment Ain't What It's Cracked Up to Be".

As well as editing a number of books on the topic of [[consciousness]] and [[mysticism]], Forman has worked as co-editor of the [[Journal of Consciousness Studies]]. He has also collaborated with [[Ken Wilber]] on work (Forman, Wilber & Andresen, 2000).

== Philosophical stance ==
Forman describes his position as "perennial psychology",{{refn|group=note|A term which appears to originate with [[Ken Wilber]]}} but he is keen to point out that this is not the same as [[perennial philosophy]].{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}

===Criticism of constructivism===
Forman has taken a strong stance against Katz' ''constructivism'', and can be understood as a defender of the perennialist position on [[mystical experience]], the view that there is indeed a core experience common to mystics of all creeds, cultures and generations.{{sfn|Forman|1990}} Notable representatives of this perennial philosophy school, such as [[William James]], [[Evelyn Underhill]], [[James Bissett Pratt]], [[Mircea Eliade]] and [[Walter Terence Stace]],{{refn|group=note|''Philosophy and Mysticism'' (1961)}} argue that mystical experience gives a direct contact with an absolute reality, which is thereafter interpreted according to one's religious and cultural background.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=3}}

This position has been strongly criticised by constructivists,{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=4}} most strongly and influently by [[Steven T. Katz]], starting with his 1978 publication ''Mysticism and Pholosophical Analysis''.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=9}}<!--START OF NOTE-->{{refn|group=note|According to Forman, constructivism is based on three interconnected theses:{{sfn|Katz|1990|p=9}}
# The constructivist these, which states that mystical experiences are mediated: "The [mystical] experience itself as well as the form in which it is reported is shaped by concepts which the mystic brings to, and which shape, his experience."{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=10}}
# An unstated presupposition, namely that religious traditions provide the set of beliefs and concepts with which these experiences are mediated.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=10}}
# The pluralism thesis, namely that experiences of different persons will have different experiences, due to their different religious background.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=10}}

According to Forman, three versions of constructivism can be discerned:{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=13-14}} 
# Complete constructivism, which states that mystical experience is completely shaped by the set of religious doctrines and expectations;
# Incomplete constructivism, which states that part of the experience is provided by religious doctrines and expectations, and part is provided by something else, such as sensory input;
# Catalytic constructivism, which states that specific beliefs will lead to the practice of mystical practices, which in turn leads to mystical experiences.}}<!--END OF NOTE--> According to Forman, these criticisms center around three points:{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=4}}
# Perennialists have a naive and mistaken methodology in their approach of primary texts, which are mistranslated, quoted out of context, and misinterpreted;
# Perennialists assume an underlying similarity without proving this. Their assumptions are the starting point for presenting quotes which superficially sound the same, without a thorough and careful analysis of these quotes and their context;
# Perennialists are hermenuetically naive. They merely "divine" the experiences on which these texts are supposedly based, without a proper philosophical or methodological argument for the move from text to the postulated experience behind it.

Forman has criticised the constructivist stance, specifically criticising Katz article ''Language, Epistemology and Mysticism'' (1978).{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=15}} According to Forman, Katz commits the fallacy of ''petitio principii'', that is, making a statement without providing evidence, but only providing arguments.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=15-16}} According to Forman, Katz' argument is systematically incomplete, since it implies that any difference in religious beliefs and assumptions leads to different experiences. Yet, according to Forman, the same experience may be described in different terms, such as ''samadhi'' and ''[[sunyata]]''.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=16-18}}

Forman further criticises Katz for his inability to take into account novel experiences, of persons who are not trained in mystical traditions, which resemble trained mystical experiences, yet are not invoked by mystical practices.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=9-25}} According to Forman, one can have a mystical experience, and only later recognise it as similar to those acquired in mystical traditions.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=19-21}}

===Pure Consciousness Event===

====Description of PCE====
Forman defines [[mysticism]] as "a set of experiences or more precisely, conscious events, which are not described in terms of sensory experience or mental images."{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=7}}{{refn|group=note|This is a limited definition of "mysticism." Mystical traditions typically aim at a transformation of the human personality; socalled "mystical experiences" are only a subpart of this developmental trajectory.}} Following [[Roland Fischer]], Forman makes a distinction between ergotropic and trophotropic mystical states.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=5-7}} Ergotropic mystical states are hallucinations, visions and auditory experiences, whereas samadhi and other wakefull states are tropotropic.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=5-6}} Forman restricts the term "mysticism" to the tropotropic states.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=7}}

Forman argues that there is a phenomenon which he calls the "Pure Consciousness Event," a "wakefull though contentless (nonintentional) consciousness."{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=8}} It is the same as [[samadhi]], and a form of Walter Stace's [[Mystical experience#Walter T. Stace – extroverted and introverted mysticism|introvertive mysticism]].{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=8}} In [[transcendental meditation]], it is called [[Turiya|transcendental consciousness]];{{sfn|Williamson|2010|p=182}} it is the fourth of seven states of consciousness, and the first of four transcendental states of consciousness, which eventually end in full [[Enlightenment (spirituality)|enlightenment]].{{sfn|Williamson|2010|p=182}}<ref group=web>[http://tmhome.com/books-videos/7-states-of-consciousness-video-interview/ ''7 levels of consciousness: The path of enlightenment'']</ref>{{refn|group=note|See also [http://www.drfredtravis.com/HSC%20summary.html Fred Travis, ''Summary of Research on Higher States of Consciousness'']}}

According to [[James H. Austin]], commenting on Forman's descriptions of his personal experiences with this sense of silence and bottomlessness, Forman also stated that although background thoughts disappeared, there was also an "element of promise," "a gratuitous ''[[subconscious]]'' process of ''[[incubation (psychology)|incubation]]''." Forman himself gives the example of a student who asks him a question: "Although he is aware that his conscious mind is "completely silent," yet the correct answer still pops up to the surface of his mind out of the background of this "richly pregnant silence.""{{sfn|Austin|2014|p=84}}

Forman equates sahaja samadhi with Stace's extroverted mysticism, noting that Stace considered "introverted mysticism" to be a higher form of mysticism than "extroverted mysticism." Forman disagrees, referring to [[Ramana Maharshi]], who repeatedly stated that [[sahaja samadhi]], effortless samadhi, was a further development than samadhi, absorption. {{sfn|Forman|1990|p=8}} The same stance is taken in transcendental meditation, where the highest stages of consciousness continue throughout waking activity.{{sfn|Williamson|2010|p=183}}{{refn|group=note|Williamson nothes that "[m]ost TM-practitioners struggled to understand how their own experience fit with Maharishi's blueprint."{{sfn|Williamson|2010|p=183}}}}

According to Forman, constructivism is not able to account for the PCE as being a constructed event.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=21}} According to Forman, a mystical experience may be shaped or constructed in three senses: content, form, shaping-process.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=22}} All three fail for the PCE:
# Form: PCE's are contentless, and therefore not shaped by "forms" or "schemata."{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=22-23}}
# Content: PCE's are contentless; they can also occur in neophytes;{{refn|group=note|Though oe may wonder if these "novel," satori-like experiences, are the same as Forman's PCE's.}}and they occur in various mystical traditions, despite their differences in states of religious beliefs and expectations.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=23-24}}
# Shaping-process: PCE's are not a series of events which shape each other, but are a continuous event of the same experience.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=24-26}}{{refn|group=note|Forman ignores the role of guru's in leading their students in their meditative experiences, thereby encouraging specific experiences and discouraging other experiences. He also i the sequgnores here the sequence of experiences as in the Buddhist [[Dhyāna in Buddhism|jhanas]] and in Patanjali's eigtht-limb yoga as described in ''[[Yoga Sutras of Patanjali]]''. He does mention those stages, though, in defense of the PCE, as they lead to the PCE.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=23}}}}

Forman describes the stages leading to the PCE, such as the Buddhist formless jhanas, as a series of successive stages in which cognitive schemata are "forgotten," leading to an "empty" state of consciousness.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=23}}

Forman questions the doctrine of [[intentionality]] insofar as he claims that, during a Pure Consciousness Event, cognition may lack an intentional object.{{sfn|Forman|1999|p=67}}

====Criticism====
Lola Williamson interviewed TM-practitioners. In contrast to Forman's statements she notes that those transcendent experiences show variations between various TM-practitioners, and are also not contentless.{{sfn|Williamson|2010|p=174}}

Yaroslav Komarovski (2015) notes that the idea of a PCE has a very limited applicability in [[Tibetan Buddhism]].{{sfn|Komarovski|2015|p=78}} According to Komarovski, the realization of [[Sunyata|emptiness]] as described in the Buddhist [[Madhyamaka]] tradition is different from the PCE. Not only the realization itself is different, but also the causes and the subsequent influence on the personality.{{sfn|Komarovski|2015|p=76}} According to Komarovski, it is brought about by specific Buddhist techniques, and results in specific Buddhist objectives, thereby illustrating the opposite of what Forman argues.{{sfn|Komarovski|2015|p=76}} According to Komarovski, to force the PCE into the spectrum of Tibetan Buddhist practices, it would be, at best, one of the minor events, and not the key mystical experience.{{sfn|Komarovski|2015|p=77}} Rather, according to Komarvski, "certain experiences and mental states adresses by Tibetan thinkers are treated as PCE due to an oversimplification of and confusion about the nature of those experiences."{{sfn|Komarovski|2015|p=77}}

== Works ==

===''The Innate Capacity''===
In ''The Innate Capacity'', he gives the example of a man who had the [[Buddhist]] experience of [[satori]], although not himself a [[Buddhist]] at the time, and only later learnt about [[satori]].{{sfn|Forman|1998}}{{refn|group=note|The same casus is mentioned in ''The Problem of Pure Consciousness''.{{sfn|Forman|1990|p=20}} Forman includes such spontaneous ''mystical experiences'' within ''mysticism'', the historical traditions which train people to undergo such experiences, and to integrate them in a larger transformation of the personality.}} Indeed, even if one did learn about an experience and later have it, in Forman's view this does not prove that the learning causes the experience; to think in this way would, in Forman's view, be to commit the logical error of [[post hoc ergo propter hoc]].{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}

===''Enlightenment Ain't What It's Cracked Up to Be''===
''Enlightenment Ain't What It's Cracked Up to Be'', Forman's most popular book, is his most personal book. Using his own experience as a touchstone, the volume is an exploration into the experiential nuances of and nature of spiritual enlightenment. Forman describes both the illusions that many gurus have communicated about it, and the nature of the disillusionment process. Tapping his own 40 years of experience of such a permanent shift, Forman describes the long term value of enlightenment as he came to view it: the honesty and authenticity that it serves to encourage. The book teaches however mostly through its tone of honesty and authentic seeking, offering a teaching through the quality of writing and openness.{{sfn|Forman|2011}}

